                        <h1 class="- topic/title title topictitle1" css:bookmark-level="1" css:color="rgb(0 , 191 , 111)" css:display="block" css:font-size="24px" css:margin-bottom="20px" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="H1" css:page-break-after="avoid" id="ariaid-title1"><css:bookmark-label><css:content source="before"/><css:content source="text"/></css:bookmark-label><span class="- topic/ph topic/title-wrapper ph title-wrapper" css:display="inline">Oregon Trust Code</span></h1>
                        <div class="- topic/body body" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="0" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0">
                            <p class="- topic/shortdesc shortdesc" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">The Oregon Trust Code is a set of regulations
                                that govern the creation, modification, and administration of trusts
                                in the state of Oregon, including banking trusts.</p>
                            <div class="- topic/note note caution note_caution" css:background-image="url('file:/C:/Program%20Files/Oxygen%20XML%20Editor%2024/frameworks/dita/DITA-OT3.x/plugins/com.oxygenxml.webhelp.responsive/oxygen-webhelp/app/img/caution.svg')" css:background-position="0.5em 0.5em" css:background-repeat="no-repeat" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="Note" css:padding-bottom="0.75em" css:padding-left="3em" css:padding-right="0.5em" css:padding-top="0.75em" type="caution"><span class="note__title" css:display="inline" css:font-weight="bold" css:page-break-after="avoid">CAUTION:</span> The following information only pertains to
                                individuals who open Pine Vista Bank products in the state of
                                Oregon.</div>
                            <section class="- topic/section section" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="Sect" id="ToPutItPlainly">
                                <h2 class="- topic/title title sectiontitle" css:bookmark-level="2" css:bookmark-state="closed" css:display="block" css:font-size="1.17em" css:font-weight="bold" css:margin-bottom="0" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="H2" css:page-break-after="avoid"><css:bookmark-label><css:content source="before"/><css:content source="text"/></css:bookmark-label>To
                                    Put It Plainly</h2>
                                <ul class="- topic/ul ul" css:display="block" css:list-style-type="disc" css:margin-bottom="1.33em" css:margin-top="1.33em" css:padding-left="40px">
                                    <li class="- topic/li li" css:display="list-item">The Oregon
                                        Trust Code, established in 2005, is designed to govern all
                                        aspects of trust administration in the state of Oregon.</li>
                                    <li class="- topic/li li" css:display="list-item">The Code
                                        covers a wide range of topics related to trusts, including
                                        their creation, modification, and termination, as well as
                                        the duties and powers of trustees and the rights of
                                        beneficiaries.</li>
                                    <li class="- topic/li li" css:display="list-item">By providing a
                                        clear and comprehensive framework for trust administration,
                                        the Oregon Trust Code aims to ensure that trustees adhere to
                                        certain standards of conduct and that the rights of
                                        beneficiaries are protected.</li>
                                    <li class="- topic/li li" css:display="list-item">For banks and
                                        other financial institutions involved in the administration
                                        of trusts, the Oregon Trust Code provides clear guidelines
                                        and standards to follow, creating obligations to
                                        beneficiaries and providing mechanisms for resolving
                                        disputes related to trusts.</li>
                                </ul>
                            </section>
                            <section class="- topic/section section" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="Sect" id="History">
                                <h2 class="- topic/title title sectiontitle" css:bookmark-level="2" css:bookmark-state="closed" css:display="block" css:font-size="1.17em" css:font-weight="bold" css:margin-bottom="0" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="H2" css:page-break-after="avoid"><css:bookmark-label><css:content source="before"/><css:content source="text"/></css:bookmark-label>History</h2>
                                <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">The Oregon Trust Code was introduced in 2005 as part of a
                                    comprehensive effort by the state of Oregon to provide clear and
                                    modern rules governing the creation and administration of
                                    trusts. The Code incorporated the vast majority of provisions of
                                    the Uniform Trust Code, a model law created by the Uniform Law
                                    Commission, thereby aligning Oregon's trust law with the laws of
                                    many other states.</p>
                                <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">Over the years, the Oregon Trust Code has been revised and
                                    updated in response to emerging trends and issues in trust law,
                                    further strengthening Oregon's framework for trust
                                    administration.</p>
                            </section>
                            <section class="- topic/section section" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="Sect" id="ReasonForCreation">
                                <h2 class="- topic/title title sectiontitle" css:bookmark-level="2" css:bookmark-state="closed" css:display="block" css:font-size="1.17em" css:font-weight="bold" css:margin-bottom="0" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="H2" css:page-break-after="avoid"><css:bookmark-label><css:content source="before"/><css:content source="text"/></css:bookmark-label>Reason
                                    for Creation</h2>
                                <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">The Oregon Trust Code was created to provide a comprehensive
                                    and modern legal framework for trust administration in the state
                                    of Oregon. Prior to the Code's enactment, trust law in Oregon
                                    was based on a mix of statutes and common law, which could be
                                    unclear or outdated. The Code aimed to resolve these issues by
                                    providing clear, up-to-date rules that cover all aspects of
                                    trust administration.</p>
                                <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">The Code also sought to standardize Oregon's trust law with
                                    that of other states by incorporating the majority of provisions
                                    of the Uniform Trust Code. This standardization is beneficial
                                    for trustees, beneficiaries, and attorneys who operate in
                                    multiple states.</p>
                            </section>
                            <section class="- topic/section section" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="Sect" id="Impact">
                                <h2 class="- topic/title title sectiontitle" css:bookmark-level="2" css:bookmark-state="closed" css:display="block" css:font-size="1.17em" css:font-weight="bold" css:margin-bottom="0" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="1em" css:oxy-pdf-tag-type="H2" css:page-break-after="avoid"><css:bookmark-label><css:content source="before"/><css:content source="text"/></css:bookmark-label>Consumer
                                    and Trust Beneficiary Impact</h2>
                                <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">The Oregon Trust Code has a significant impact on trust
                                    creators (known as <a class="- topic/xref xref" css:color="rgb(213 , 81 , 33)" css:display="inline" css:link="glossary0801.html#glossary0801__gloss_set" href="glossary0801.html#glossary0801__gloss_set" type="p">"settlors"</a>), trustees, and trust beneficiaries in
                                    Oregon. The Code provides clear rules that govern the
                                    administration of trusts, influencing both the creation of new
                                    trusts and the management of existing ones. </p>
                                <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">Here are some of the most frequently impacted areas:</p>
                                <ul class="- topic/ul ul" css:display="block" css:list-style-type="disc" css:margin-bottom="1.33em" css:margin-top="1.33em" css:padding-left="40px">
                                    <li class="- topic/li li" css:display="list-item">
                                        <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em"><strong class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ph b" css:display="inline" css:font-weight="bold">Trust Creation:</strong> The
                                            Code provides clear rules for creating a trust in
                                            Oregon. This impacts settlors, who can use these rules
                                            to ensure their trust is valid and accomplishes their
                                            intended objectives.</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li class="- topic/li li" css:display="list-item">
                                        <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em"><strong class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ph b" css:display="inline" css:font-weight="bold">Trust
                                                Administration:</strong> The Code governs how
                                            trustees must administer trusts. This impacts trustees,
                                            who must follow these rules in their management of the
                                            trust, and beneficiaries, whose rights and interests are
                                            protected by the trustees' compliance with these
                                            rules.</p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li class="- topic/li li" css:display="list-item">
                                        <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em"><strong class="+ topic/ph hi-d/b ph b" css:display="inline" css:font-weight="bold">Dispute Resolution:</strong>
                                            The Code provides mechanisms for resolving disputes over
                                            trusts. This impacts trustees and beneficiaries, who may
                                            use these mechanisms to resolve conflicts over the
                                            interpretation of the trust or the trustee's
                                            administration of the trust.</p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                                <p class="- topic/p p" css:display="block" css:margin-bottom="1em" css:margin-left="0" css:margin-right="0" css:margin-top="0.5em">While these rules can create additional obligations for
                                    trustees, they serve a critical role in protecting the rights
                                    and interests of beneficiaries and ensuring the effective
                                    administration of trusts.</p>
                            </section>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
